g","square_large-width":520,"square_large-height":520}},"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p>The nature of infinity makes this seeming increase possible. Turning the entire East group West erases all the last East rotations. So what remains?</p>
<p>No West-ending paths preceded the final Easts because backtracking wasn’t allowed. But an infinite number of East-ending paths preceded those final East turns (no rule forbids making East-East your last two rotations). An infinite number of paths ending with Norths and Souths did, too. Merely by rotating the entire East group West, we’ve turned it into a group that contains all East, North and South points. All the starting points are in there now, too (because every path consisting of just one East turn has now returned to its origin).</p>
<p>At this point we’ve duplicated all the points in three of the six groups (North, South and starting points). Next, we just need to duplicate the other three groups (East, West and poles/center). The first two are easy: Just rotate the North group South, which gives you all North, East and West points.</p>
<div id='component-612bbd22731d4' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-612bbd22731d4","data":{"id":108267,"src":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4.jpg","alt":"A graphic showing how rotating the \u200bNorth group \u200bSouth duplicates the \u200bEast, \u200bWest and \u200bNorth groups, and the starting points.","class":"","width":1120,"height":504,"mobileSrc":{"ID":108266,"id":108266,"title":"Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE","filename":"Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE.jpg","filesize":281702,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE.jpg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/how-a-mathematical-paradox-allows-infinite-cloning-20210826\/banach-tarski-4-mobile\/","alt":"A graphic showing how rotating the \u200bNorth group \u200bSouth duplicates the \u200bEast, \u200bWest and \u200bNorth groups, and the starting points.","author":"13691","description":"","caption":"","name":"banach-tarski-4-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":108105,"date":"2021-08-26 13:17:49","modified":"2021-08-26 13:49:37","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/jpeg","type":"image","subtype":"jpeg","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":1120,"height":504,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE-520x234.jpg","thumbnail-width":520,"thumbnail-height":234,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE.jpg","medium-width":1120,"medium-height":504,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE-768x346.jpg","medium_large-width":768,"medium_large-height":346,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE.jpg","large-width":1120,"large-height":504,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE-160x160.jpg","square_small-width":160,"square_small-height":160,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-MOBILE-520x504.jpg","square_large-width":520,"square_large-height":504}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":["default"],"disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":{"ID":108267,"id":108267,"title":"Banach-Tarski-4","filename":"Banach-Tarski-4.jpg","filesize":273602,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4.jpg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/how-a-mathematical-paradox-allows-infinite-cloning-20210826\/banach-tarski-4\/","alt":"A graphic showing how rotating the \u200bNorth group \u200bSouth duplicates the \u200bEast, \u200bWest and \u200bNorth groups, and the starting points.","author":"13691","description":"","caption":"","name":"banach-tarski-4","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":108105,"date":"2021-08-26 13:17:50","modified":"2021-08-26 13:49:39","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/jpeg","type":"image","subtype":"jpeg","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":1120,"height":504,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-520x234.jpg","thumbnail-width":520,"thumbnail-height":234,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4.jpg","medium-width":1120,"medium-height":504,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-768x346.jpg","medium_large-width":768,"medium_large-height":346,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4.jpg","large-width":1120,"large-height":504,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-160x160.jpg","square_small-width":160,"square_small-height":160,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-4-520x504.jpg","square_large-width":520,"square_large-height":504}},"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p>Finally, we need to duplicate the poles and the center point. This occurs through a process similar to that of another infinity-related argument called Hilbert’s hotel, devised by David Hilbert in 1924, the same year Banach and Tarski came up with their paradox.</p>
<p>In this thought experiment, imagine a hotel with an infinite number of rooms. Suppose that only Room 43 is empty. Take every guest in Room 44 and above and move them down one room. You’ve filled the vacancy without creating a new one (because when you shift infinite guests over one room, there’s always a guest to replace the one you just moved).</p>
<div id='component-612bbd227a700' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-612bbd227a700","data":{"id":108269,"src":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5.jpg","alt":"A graphic with hotel doors depicting the Hilbert\u2019s Hotel argument.","class":"","width":1120,"height":546,"mobileSrc":{"ID":108268,"id":108268,"title":"Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE","filename":"Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE.jpg","filesize":99148,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE.jpg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/how-a-mathematical-paradox-allows-infinite-cloning-20210826\/banach-tarski-5-mobile\/","alt":"A graphic with hotel doors depicting the Hilbert\u2019s Hotel argument.","author":"13691","description":"","caption":"","name":"banach-tarski-5-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":108105,"date":"2021-08-26 13:17:51","modified":"2021-08-26 13:49:47","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/jpeg","type":"image","subtype":"jpeg","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":1120,"height":546,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE-520x254.jpg","thumbnail-width":520,"thumbnail-height":254,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE.jpg","medium-width":1120,"medium-height":546,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE-768x374.jpg","medium_large-width":768,"medium_large-height":374,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE.jpg","large-width":1120,"large-height":546,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE-160x160.jpg","square_small-width":160,"square_small-height":160,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-MOBILE-520x520.jpg","square_large-width":520,"square_large-height":520}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":["default"],"disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":{"ID":108269,"id":108269,"title":"Banach-Tarski-5","filename":"Banach-Tarski-5.jpg","filesize":92550,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5.jpg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/how-a-mathematical-paradox-allows-infinite-cloning-20210826\/banach-tarski-5\/","alt":"A graphic with hotel doors depicting the Hilbert\u2019s Hotel argument.","author":"13691","description":"","caption":"","name":"banach-tarski-5","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":108105,"date":"2021-08-26 13:17:51","modified":"2021-08-26 13:49:45","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/jpeg","type":"image","subtype":"jpeg","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":1120,"height":546,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-520x254.jpg","thumbnail-width":520,"thumbnail-height":254,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5.jpg","medium-width":1120,"medium-height":546,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-768x374.jpg","medium_large-width":768,"medium_large-height":374,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5.jpg","large-width":1120,"large-height":546,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-160x160.jpg","square_small-width":160,"square_small-height":160,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-5-520x520.jpg","square_large-width":520,"square_large-height":520}},"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p>Now imagine the missing set of poles as vacancies dotting different lines of latitude on the duplicate sphere. Shift all the points on each line of latitude over, and infinity fills the vacancies.</p>
<div id='component-612bbd2282ef3' class=''><script type="text/template">{"type":"Image","id":"component-612bbd2282ef3","data":{"id":108271,"src":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6.jpg","alt":"A graphic explaining how the argument from Hilbert\u2019s Hotel \u200bcan be used to fill vacant points on a circle.","class":"","width":1120,"height":690,"mobileSrc":{"ID":108270,"id":108270,"title":"Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE","filename":"Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE.jpg","filesize":90399,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE.jpg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/how-a-mathematical-paradox-allows-infinite-cloning-20210826\/banach-tarski-6-mobile\/","alt":"A graphic explaining how the argument from Hilbert\u2019s Hotel \u200bcan be used to fill vacant points on a circle.","author":"13691","description":"","caption":"","name":"banach-tarski-6-mobile","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":108105,"date":"2021-08-26 13:17:52","modified":"2021-08-26 13:49:52","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/jpeg","type":"image","subtype":"jpeg","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":1120,"height":690,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE-520x320.jpg","thumbnail-width":520,"thumbnail-height":320,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE.jpg","medium-width":1120,"medium-height":690,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE-768x473.jpg","medium_large-width":768,"medium_large-height":473,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE.jpg","large-width":1120,"large-height":690,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE-160x160.jpg","square_small-width":160,"square_small-height":160,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-MOBILE-520x520.jpg","square_large-width":520,"square_large-height":520}},"zoomSrc":false,"mobileZoomSrc":false,"align":"align=\"inline\"","wrapper_width":"","caption":"","attribution":"","variant":"shortcode","size":["default"],"disableZoom":true,"disableMobileZoom":true,"srcImage":{"ID":108271,"id":108271,"title":"Banach-Tarski-6","filename":"Banach-Tarski-6.jpg","filesize":87151,"url":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6.jpg","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/how-a-mathematical-paradox-allows-infinite-cloning-20210826\/banach-tarski-6\/","alt":"A graphic explaining how the argument from Hilbert\u2019s Hotel \u200bcan be used to fill vacant points on a circle.","author":"13691","description":"","caption":"","name":"banach-tarski-6","status":"inherit","uploaded_to":108105,"date":"2021-08-26 13:17:53","modified":"2021-08-26 13:49:54","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/jpeg","type":"image","subtype":"jpeg","icon":"https:\/\/api.quantamagazine.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":1120,"height":690,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-520x320.jpg","thumbnail-width":520,"thumbnail-height":320,"medium":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6.jpg","medium-width":1120,"medium-height":690,"medium_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-768x473.jpg","medium_large-width":768,"medium_large-height":473,"large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6.jpg","large-width":1120,"large-height":690,"square_small":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-160x160.jpg","square_small-width":160,"square_small-height":160,"square_large":"https:\/\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\/uploads\/2021\/08\/Banach-Tarski-6-520x520.jpg","square_large-width":520,"square_large-height":520}},"largeForPrint":false,"externalLink":"","original_resolution":false}}</script></div>
<p>The vacant center point exists on another circle that can be filled the same way. As a result, voila! We’ve duplicated all six groups. We can now combine each set of six groups into its own sphere.</p>
<p>The outcome feels impossible. How can you double the volume of an object just by decomposing and rearranging it? One explanation is that Banach-Tarski offloads the burden of uncountability. Decomposing the sphere with sequential rotations, like counting off natural numbers, creates a more manageable workspace — a more manageable infinity than the uncountable one plaguing the initial sphere.</p>
<p>The paradox has detractors. Some see it as an absurd conclusion that points to a flaw in the rules of mathematical reasoning that enable it.</p>
<p>“It’s like a bellwether,” said <a href="https://web.maths.unsw.edu.au/~norman/">Norman Wildberger</a>, a recently retired professor of mathematics at the University of New South Wales in Sydney, Australia. “It’s like a massive red flag.”</p>
<p>The mathematical rule that makes the Banach-Tarski paradox possible is called the axiom of choice. It’s one of nine axioms in a system called Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory, or ZFC, that serves as the foundation of modern mathematics.</p>
<div id='component-612bbd22838b9' class='related-list'><script type="text/template">{"type":"LinkList","id":"component-612bbd22838b9","data":{"title":"Related:","class":"related-list","links":[{"type":"internal","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/how-many-numbers-exist-infinity-proof-moves-math-closer-to-an-answer-20210715\/","title":"How Many Numbers Exist? Infinity Proof Moves Math Closer to an Answer."},{"type":"internal","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/mathematicians-measure-infinities-find-theyre-equal-20170912\/","title":"Mathematicians Measure Infinities and Find They\u2019re Equal"},{"type":"internal","link":"https:\/\/www.quantamagazine.org\/to-settle-infinity-question-a-new-law-of-mathematics-20131126\/","title":"To Settle Infinity Dispute, a New Law of Logic"}]}}</script></div>
<p>In the historical development of ZFC, the axiom of choice is sometimes viewed as an add-on to the other eight — a status that makes it vulnerable to criticism when it enables outcomes like the Banach-Tarski paradox. The axiom of choice grants mathematicians the power to “choose” an item from each bin of a collection, even if that collection is infinite. This makes Banach-Tarski a Rorschach test for working with infinity: Many see the paradox as wondrous; critics like Wildberger cringe.</p>
<p>But most mathematicians don’t lose sleep over the axiom of choice. They see the Banach-Tarski paradox as a demonstration of the richness of mathematics. It offers a law-abiding example of how math can stray from physical intuition without contradicting itself.</p>
<p>“Almost anything can be doubled — can be decomposed into two things of the same cardinality,” said Sinapova.</p>
